		Comment <a href="#c_1713718917">2</a> by Raymond Camden
		posted on 10/13/2009 at 6:30 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p><a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2FCFLib.org%3AWOdcErJNG97LPvefvtc2ezLtDsI&amp;cuid=3321886" rel="nofollow noopener" title="CFLib.org">CFLib.org</a> is specifically for UDFs. UDFs are very specific forms of code that perform functions.</p><p>A cookbook is more broad. It's meant to answer basic questions. "How do I read a file in ColdFusion?" "How do I read mp3 information in ColdFusion?" Or in general, "How do I do X?" where X is something that has mass appeal. Not something like "I've got an error on line 5 of my file foo.cfm, can you fix it?"</p><p>The answer to these questions may involve UDFs, or functions built into CF, or CFCs, or may not even involve code at all. So for example, a question about securing the admin would involve a discussion of the security options of the CF Admin.</p><p>Hope this helps.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
